    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-05T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-05T22:00:00-05:00" n="31"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d31">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15 a 1/165: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-06T12:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 6, 1927—noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received April 6—10:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>50. Embassy’s telegrams 47, April 2, noon; and 49, April 2, 9 p.m.<note n="26"
                        xml:id="d31fn26">Neither printed.</note> Minister for Foreign Affairs has
                    informed me that in addition to Saito,<note n="27" xml:id="d31fn27">Admiral
                        Viscount Saito, Governor General of Korea.</note> Viscount Ishii, Japanese
                    Ambassador to France, has accepted position on delegation. These two will be
                    principal delegates, accompanied by Saburi<note n="28" xml:id="d31fn28">Mr.
                        Sadao Saburi, Chief of the Treaty Section, Japanese Foreign Office.</note>
                    as political expert and secretary to delegation, with Vice Admiral Kobayashi and
                    Bear Admiral Hara as naval experts.</p>
                <p>While plans not definitely settled it seems probable that delegates will leave
                    Japan April 25th, proceeding via Suez and due Geneva early June. Full
                    biographical data members delegation goes forward first pouch.<note n="29"
                        xml:id="d31fn29">Despatch not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
